#0  0x00005555555557a1 in main (/home/user/build/prog 0x7fffff227930)
   from /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2

main() {
    int len = strlen(vars->str);
    printf("%s\n", vars->str + len);
}

Observed symptom: memory access outside the bounds of the `vars->str` array.
The bug arises from accessing `vars->str` with an index `len` that exceeds the array's bounds, resulting in an out-of-bounds memory access.

ROOT CAUSE: 
program.c:25: Accessing `vars->str` with an out-of-bounds index `len` due to incorrect length calculation.

LOCAL FIX: 
```c
int len = strlen(vars->str);
printf("%s\n", vars->str); // Remove the out-of-bounds access
```

GLOBAL FIX: 
Replace `printf("%s\n", vars->str + len);` with `printf("%s\n", vars->str);`. The `strlen` function already calculates the length of the string, including the null-terminator. Accessing `vars->str + len` skips the null-terminator and leads to undefined behavior.













STACKTRACE:
#0  0x00005555555557a1 in main (/home/user/build/prog 0x7fffff227930)
   from /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2

main() {
    char *str = " BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB";
    size_t len = strlen(str);
    printf("%s\n", str + len);
}

Observed symptom: memory access outside the bounds of the `str` array.
The bug arises from accessing `str` with an index `len` that exceeds the array's bounds, resulting in an out-of-bounds memory access.

ROOT CAUSE: 
program.c:25: Accessing `str` with an out-of-bounds index `len` due to incorrect length calculation.

LOCAL FIX: 
```c
char *str = " BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB";
size_t len = strlen(str);
printf("%s\n", str); // Remove the out-of-bounds access
```

GLOBAL FIX: 
Replace `printf("%s\n", str + len);` with `printf("%s\n", str);`. The `strlen` function already calculates the length of the string, including the null-terminator. Accessing `str + len` skips the null-terminator and leads to undefined behavior. 

This is due to the null-terminator being included in the `strlen` count. The correct fix is to print the original `str` pointer, not the pointer to the character after the last valid character.

